<h1>LG Washer Door Boot Seal Replacement</h1>

<p>The rubber door boot seal on a front-load LG washer takes a beating — it traps water, grows mold, and eventually tears or leaks onto your floor. We replace the door boot seal same-day across LA, $250–320 with an OEM gasket and a one-year warranty, and we set it so it actually seals instead of weeping at the bottom. Call (323) 990-7550.</p>

<h2>Signs Your Door Seal Needs Replacing</h2>
<p>The usual sign is water on the floor at the front of the machine during a wash — our guide to an <a href="/washer/symptoms/lg-washer-leaking/">LG washer leaking water</a> covers how we confirm it's the boot and not a hose. Beyond leaks, look for tears or cracks in the rubber, mold and a musty smell that won't scrub out, or laundry snagging on a torn edge of the gasket. Once the boot is split or hardened, no amount of cleaning brings the seal back.</p>

<h2>How We Replace the Door Boot Seal</h2>
<p>Our techs pull the front panel and release the retaining bands — a spring-tensioned clamp at the front and another behind the boot — then work the old gasket out and clean the lip it seats against. We fit the new OEM boot and seat it carefully top and bottom so it grips evenly all the way around. It's about a 60–90 minute job, and the seating is the whole point: a boot that isn't set right weeps at the lower edge.</p>

<h2>Cost of Door Seal Replacement</h2>
<p>Door boot seal replacement runs $250–320 installed with an OEM gasket, and the $65 diagnostic is waived when you approve the repair. For the full breakdown of what drives that price, see our <a href="/washer/price-list/lg-washer-door-seal-replacement-cost/">LG washer door seal replacement cost</a> page.</p>

<h2>Keeping the New Seal Clean</h2>
<p>A fresh boot lasts far longer with a little care. Leave the door ajar between washes so the rubber dries out instead of trapping water, wipe the fold dry now and then, and use the recommended amount of HE detergent — heavy suds and standing water are what breed the mold that destroys boots early.</p>

<h2>OEM Parts and Warranty</h2>
<p>We fit OEM door boots, not aftermarket gaskets that fit loosely and leak, and back the work with a one-year warranty on parts and labor. There's no surcharge for same-day or weekend service.</p>

<p>Leaking from the door? Our LG Dryer Repair techs confirm the source and replace the boot on-site across LA, Orange County, and Ventura County — most are same-day. Call (323) 990-7550; the $65 diagnostic is waived when you approve the repair.</p>

<h2>Frequently Asked Questions — LG Washer Door Seal Replacement</h2>

<h3>How do I know if my LG washer door seal needs replacing?</h3>
<p>A failing LG washer door seal leaks water from the front during the cycle, shows tears or cracks in the rubber, or holds mold and odor that won't scrub out. Once the boot is torn or hardened, cleaning won't fix it — it needs replacing.</p>

<h3>How much does LG washer door seal replacement cost?</h3>
<p>Door boot seal replacement runs $250–320 installed with an OEM gasket. The $65 diagnostic is waived when you approve the repair, and the work has a one-year warranty. We're licensed with the Bureau of Household Goods and Services (#49573).</p>

<h3>Why does my LG washer door seal keep getting moldy?</h3>
<p>Front-load seals trap a little water in the folds after every wash, and a closed door plus too much detergent turns that into mold. Leaving the door ajar between washes, wiping the boot dry, and using the right amount of HE detergent slows it down — but a seal that's already grown mold deep in the rubber usually needs replacing.</p>

<h3>How long does it take to replace an LG washer door seal?</h3>
<p>A door boot seal replacement takes about 60–90 minutes, and we do it same-day in most cases. The time goes into seating the new boot correctly with its retaining bands so it seals instead of leaking at the bottom.</p>

<h3>Can I replace the LG washer door seal myself?</h3>
<p>It's possible but fiddly — the retaining spring bands are under tension and the boot has to be seated perfectly top and bottom or it leaks. Most DIY attempts end up weeping at the lower edge; if it's not sealed right the first time you're back to a wet floor.</p>

